        "text": "### Chemistry Insight\n\nThe dominant reaction is the formation of [NiEDTA]²⁻ with log β = **18.4**, making Ni²⁺ one of the more strongly chelated divalent transition metals by EDTA — comparable to Cu²⁺ (log β ≈ 18.8) and significantly stronger than Mn²⁺ (log β ≈ 13.8). The two networks differ in ionic strength (≈0 M vs. ≈1 M), reflecting how activity coefficients shift the apparent stability constants — a classic consideration in analytical and environmental chemistry applications.\n\n*Source: NIST SRD-46 (Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes)*",
